In GCS there are no real folders — only buckets and blobs. 
What looks like a folder raw/online_retail.csv is just a blob with a / in its name. 
GCS uses flat namespace, folders are just a UI convenience.

GCP trial accounts have CPU quota limits per region — default is often 8 vCPUs. 
Dataproc cluster creation fails silently or with cryptic errors if quota exceeded. 
Check IAM & Admin → Quotas & System Limits, filter by 'CPUS' for your region. 
Upgrade machine type or reduce cores to fit within quota.

What is a Dataproc cluster vs a standalone Spark installation?
Dataproc cluster is a managed service by gcp where everything from cpu allocation to scaling and everything is automatic. In standalone spark installation, everything is manual and infra is also managed by us (physical infra) and it can cause high cost and less reliability. 
Dataproc also has native GCS connector built in — no extra config needed to read/write gs:// paths from Spark. Standalone Spark needs manual connector setup

Why --single-node for dev and not in production?
I tried the single node method and it hit memory pressure. and btw now there are limits in the cpu allocation for trial accounts and it doesn't show up explicitly. i struggled lot of hours on this (cluster was not creating) and finally found while checking the quotas & system limits in IAM & Admin page (checked with help of chatgpt). then i created with e2-standard4. now it runs.
GCP free trial has CPU quota limits per region — default is often 8 vCPUs. n1-standard-2 single-node needs 2, e2-standard-4 needs 4. Check IAM & Admin → Quotas if cluster creation fails silently.

What happens to the cluster after the job finishes — is it still running?
the cluster is still running and ready for upcoming jobs. 
Dataproc clusters keep running and billing even when idle. In production use ephemeral clusters — create cluster, run job, delete cluster. Or use Dataproc Serverless which auto-provisions and tears down

Why is this better than running PySpark locally?
for scaling purposes and automatic installations and also reliable cloud storage access, it is lot better than local. but it does have some latency issues while working so it looks little slower (maybe due to trial account or slow internet idk)

What is a BigQuery job and how is it different from a query?
A bigquery job includes all the tasks like extraction, loading, copying, querying. any single task is called a job. it runs asynchronously and have a unique job id. whereas a query is just execution of an sql statement.

What does load_job.result() do in the Python code?
It make sures the exection waits until the load_job is complete. 
CA: Without .result(), the script would exit immediately after submitting the job, not waiting for completion. The load would still happen in the background but you'd have no way to catch errors or confirm success. .result() blocks until the job completes and raises an exception if it fails.

What is partitioning in BigQuery and why does it matter for cost?
paritioning make query area a lot smaller. like if the partition happens with a date column and the data has 150 rows in a date, it will just search in this 150 rows when the appropriate date is given. thus skipping other thousands of rows that doesn't have this date. there by reducing lot of query time and cost.
CA: BigQuery charges by bytes scanned. Partitioning reduces bytes scanned by skipping irrelevant partitions entirely. A query on 1 day's partition out of 365 days scans 1/365th of the data — direct cost reduction.

What is clustering in BigQuery and how is it different from partitioning?
it organize data inside each partition with respect to any column other than partitioned one. it will lead to having similar values in a column of a partition and sort in a way that are closely similar values leading to faster search and reduced power consumption (cheaper)

What is a surrogate key and why is it useful?
usually a surrogate key is a unique key given to each rows to tackle duplicate values in same column (like if the table has no primary key). it usually works with combining 2 or more columns and creating a unique value (composite key).
but in dbt it will get composite and also hashing the composite value. 
*Natural keys (like CustomerID) can change or be reused across systems. Surrogate key is system-generated, never changes, and uniquely identifies a row regardless of source system changes. Essential in data warehouses where you merge data from multiple sources.

What is the difference between dbt built-in tests and dbt_expectations tests?
dbt built in tests are limited with not_null, unique and similar simple conditions. but with dbt_expectations, we can give arguments and customize the tests and there are also variety of tests like values between, length of the value and many (not aware abt others).
*dbt_expectations is based on Great Expectations library — industry standard for data quality. Knowing both shows maturity in data quality practices.

When would you use a singular test vs a schema test?
singular tests involve getting results from a query. like if it returns something, it passes. it can be any query of our choice. 
but schema tests work on conditions and not as flexible as query. it is used for standardizing the data and make it meet bare minimum expectation. 
*Singular test fails if query returns ANY rows — not passes. It's the opposite of what you said. Logic is: write a query that finds bad data. If bad data exists, rows are returned, test fails.

What does the lineage graph tell you that raw SQL can't?
lineage graph give overall view of the model and in a visual manner that raw SQL can't. it is easy to understand and clearly defines the relationships between
snapshots, stages and marts.
*Also shows impact analysis — if source table changes, lineage immediately shows which staging and mart models are affected. Critical for debugging production issues.